@ddt @emalone @mulegirl Utility -> global maxima (market/product fit, high risk). Usability & aesthetics -> local maxima (market share).

@ddt @emalone @mulegirl examples: Oculus Rift 0.1, the first iPhone in Steve Jobs‚Äô pocket, http://t.co/S7ohEUlD61, Gmail as internal proto.
@ddt @emalone @mulegirl a hacked-together product that immediately delivers value is a POC. Increasing investment in design tied to growth.
@ddt @emalone @mulegirl discoverability ~= usability here. Usability matters when you need to acquire customers you don‚Äôt know personally.
@emalone @ddt @mulegirl like classic fast/good/cheap, design allocates investment between useful/usable/beautiful. Priorities shift.
@emalone @ddt @mulegirl there‚Äôs a short ramp to diminishing returns for a consumer MVP, particularly when founders know 1st customer.
@ddt @emalone as @mulegirl has pointed out, design is a series of outcome (not solution) -focused decisions. Outcome varies by phase.
@ddt @mulegirl @emalone investment varies by iteration. Invest first in utility (MVP), then usability (as complexity grows), then visual.
